Fill and boil your #kettle{} and fill a #large saucepan{} with the boiling water on
high heat.

Meanwhile, chop the @salad potatoes{350%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel) and
add to the #saucepan{} with @ground turmeric{1/2%tsp} and @salt{0.5%tsp}.

Cook until you can easily slip a knife through, ~{12-15%minutes}, then drain in a
#colander{}.

When cooked, return to the pan (off the heat). Keep warm with the #lid{} on.

== Lamb Curry ==

Meanwhile, put a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). When hot, add
the @lamb mince{200%g} and fry until browned, breaking it up with a
#wooden spoon{} as it cooks, ~{3-4%minutes}.

While the lamb browns, halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}.

Trim the @green beans{80%g} and chop in half.

Halve the @green chilli{1/2}, deseed then finely chop.

Chop the @baby plum tomatoes{250%g} in half (or leave them whole if you prefer).

Drain any excess lamb fat, then stir the shallot and green beans into the lamb and
cook until starting to soften, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> Add a drizzle of oil if the pan looks dry.

Stir in the @ginger puree{1/2%tsp}, @North Indian style spice mix{1%tsp},
@ground turmeric{1/2%tsp}, a pinch of @?chilli{} (careful - you can always add more
later!) and the tomatoes.

Cook for ~{1%minute} before stirring in the @water{100%ml}.

Bring to the boil then reduce the heat and simmer until the beans are tender,
~{3-5%minutes} and the tomatoes have broken down.

Stir through the @mango chutney{40%g}.

> Add a splash of water if the curry is looking dry.

Season the lamb to taste with @salt{}, @pepper{} and a pinch more @?chilli{} if
needed.

Stir the @nigella seeds{1%tsp} through the drained potatoes.

== To Serve ==

Using whichever pan is largest, combine the lamb mixture with the potatoes and
gently stir to combine.

Serve in #bowls{} finished with a sprinkle more chilli if needed. Enjoy!